summary.intent: Fix Dart analysis issues in a Flutter mobile app, including resolving import ambiguities, applying automated style fixes, and documenting certificate pinning implementation.
summary.outcome: Successfully resolved the Failure class import conflict in oauth_login.dart, applied 366 automated dart fixes plus 5 manual fixes for unused variables and discarded futures, and enhanced certificate pinning documentation with SPKI extraction methods and build commands.

repo: The codebase has both core/errors/failures.dart and core/types/result.dart that export classes named 'Failure', causing import ambiguities
Flutter project uses Riverpod 3.x for state management and has comprehensive security features including certificate pinning
The app has debug mode bypasses for certificate pinning to allow development testing

code.finding: Import ambiguity resolved by hiding Failure from failures.dart since only AuthFailure was used, while result.dart's Failure and Success were both needed
Certificate pinning can use either certificate fingerprints or SPKI pins (Subject Public Key Info), with SPKI being more robust for certificate rotation
Test callbacks for rendering tests don't need to be tracked if they're not expected to be invoked - cleaner to not create the variables at all

workflow: dart fix --apply can automatically resolve hundreds of linting issues across a codebase efficiently
Manual fixes for discarded_futures warnings use unawaited() from dart:async to explicitly mark fire-and-forget async calls
flutter analyze can be filtered with grep to focus on specific error types or files
Using 'hide' or 'show' clauses on imports is the cleanest way to resolve naming conflicts between packages

friction: 768 analysis issues remain after fixes, but many are pre-existing type/API mismatch errors outside the scope of the assigned tasks
open_items: Pre-existing type and API mismatch errors in the codebase were not addressed as they were outside the scope of the three assigned tasks
Many discarded_futures infos remain across the codebase but weren't fixed due to volume and being lower priority than warnings/errors
